ed millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":82,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Guildford was born about 1300, in Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard de Guilford, was 24 and his mother, Mrs. Richard de Guildford, was 21. He married Mrs William de Guilford in 1326, in Rolvenden, Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He lived in Kent, England in 1388. He died after 1388, in Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt. 1300–Aft 1388":"umbes 1300–pärast 1388","1300–1388":"1300–1388","1304–Female":"1304–Surnud","1331–Male":"1331–Surnud","1277–Male":"1277–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","Aft 1388":"pärast 1388","1382":"1382","1280":"1280","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1304":"1304","1388":"1388","13